  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 13.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The son of Geber",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [possibly son of the Geber mentioned in ver. 19] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "in Ramothgilead",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [two districts east of the Jordan are now enumerated. And first, the territory of Gad. Bamoth-gilead was a Levitical city (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 21:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Its selection as a city of refuge (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 20:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and as the seat of Bengeber's prefecture, together with the constant wars waged for its possession (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 9:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") show that it was a position of great strength and importance]; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "him pertained the towns of Jair",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Havoth Jair are",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " strictly the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "lives",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", villages, because men ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "live",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " there) of Jair. So Gesenius, who cites ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Eisleben",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and similar names] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the son Manasseh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [it is doubtful whether the judge of that name (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 10:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") or Jair, the son of Segub (called a \"son of Manasseh\" in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", because his grandmother was a daughter of the great Machir, though his father belonged to Judah, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is intended. Probably it is the latter. (They can hardly be one and the same person, though they are often identified, as, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the Speaker's Comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 10:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But they belong to different periods.) Curiously enough, the Havoth Jair are mentioned in connexion with each (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:4, 5, 14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 10:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but in every ease except the last the reference is to the son of Segub. As the judge was probably one of his descendants, it is not surprising that the judge's sons should possess some of the villages of Jair], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "which are in Gilead; to him also pertained the region",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "חֶבֶל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", lit., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "measuring cord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", came to signify the region measured] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "of",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Argob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [elsewhere \"the Argob,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the stony. This is the region subsequently known as Trachonitis, now called the Lejah. It is distinguished here and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from the Gileadite district just mentioned, with which it is sometimes confounded. Both seem to have been conquered by Jair, but the towns of the former bore the name of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Havoth Jair",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and these of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Bashan Havoth Jair.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:4, 5, 14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The latter consisted of threescore cities, with walls, gates, and bars. This remarkable district, twenty-two miles in length by fourteen in breadth, is \"wholly composed of black basalt, which appears to have issued from innumerable pores in the earth in a liquid state .... Before cooling, its surface was violently agitated, and it was afterwards shattered and rent by convulsions .... Strange as it may seem, this ungainly and forbidding region is thickly studded with deserted cities and villages\" (Porter, \"Giant Cities of Bashan,\" also in Kitto's ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Cycl.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 3. p. 1032; Dict. Bib. 1:104)] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "which is in Bashan, threescore great cities with walls and brazen bars.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [These words are a reminiscence of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:4, 5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".] 1 Kings 4:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Bengeber was in Ramoth of Gilead in the tribe of Gad (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 20:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), probably on the site of the modern Szalt (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"To him belonged the Havvoth Jair (Jair's-lives) in Gilead, to him the region of Argob in Bashan, sixty great cities with walls and brazen bolts.\" If we look at this passage alone, the region of Argob in Bashan appears to be distinct from the Havvoth Jair in Gilead. But if we compare it with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:40-41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:4-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", it is evident from these passages that the Jair's-lives are identical with the sixty large and fortified cities of the region of Argob. For, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", these sixty fortified cities, with high walls, gates, and bars, were all fortified cities of the kingdom of Og of Bashan, which the Israelites conquered under Moses, and to which, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Jair the Manassite, who had conquered them, gave the name of Havvoth Jair. Hence it is stated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that the sixty Jair-towns were situated in Bashan. Consequently the אר חבל לו in our verse is to be taken as a more precise definition of וגו יאיר חוּת לו, or a clearer description of the district superintended by Bengeber, so that Gilead is used, as is frequently the case, in the broader sense of Peraea. Compare with this the Commentary on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the names ארגּב and חוּת are explained, and the imaginary discrepancy between the sixty Jair's-towns in the passages cited, and the twenty-three and thirty cities of Jair in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 10:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is discussed and solved. And when Thenius objects to this explanation on the ground that the villages of Jair cannot be identical with the sixty fortified cities, because villages of nomads and strongly fortified cities could not be one and the same, this objection falls to the ground with the untenable interpretation of חוּת as applying to nomad villages.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]